<br>
From what I saw in my logs, I think the formula works something like this...<br>
<br>
There are two types of hits you can score.<br>
<br>
The normal hit which uses...<br>
<br>
DB + (DI x rnd 20), which is modified somehow through a comparison of PC attack vs. mob ac for distribution, with probably some sort of limit in distribution movement in terms of +- relative to the mob.<br>
<br>
There's also an &quot;exceptional hit&quot; which appears to use an entirely different calculation which based on my observations seems to work something like this...<br>
<br>
Exceptional Hit = DB + (DI x Rnd20) + (DI x (attack/1000) x Rnd20)<br>
<br>
Maximum Hit = DB + (DI x 20) + (DI x (attack/1000) x 20)<br>
<br>
This appears to work for 1hb on a monk at lower attack ranges.  With Fist of Nature (15/1<!--EZCODE EMOTICON START 8) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/glasses.gif ALT="8)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   and 1200 attack (no avatar or epic) the calculation would  look something like this...<br>
<br>
Max Hit = 11 + (1.5 x 20) + (1.5 x (1200/1000) x 20)<br>
= 41 + (1.5 x 1.2 x 20)<br>
= 77<br>
<br>
77 happened to be my maximum observable damage with no additional buffs over a 45 minute period of meleeing various mobs.  IE, I don't believe that mob ac has any effect on the max possible damage.  I also observed different maximum damage values and a different set of data points when I put on monk Epic buff (+54 attack), or when I had Avatar (+100 attack, +100 str), or when I had both Avatar + Monk epic (There is also the possibility for error given the RNG as my datasets of each weren't huge, &lt; 1000 hits with each tested with 1hb in main, shield in offhand). <br>
<br>
So, for something like your 30/37 weapon, if we assume your attack is 1200, your exceptional and maximum possible damage should look something like this...<br>
<br>
Exceptional Hit = 30 + (3 x Rnd20) + (3 x (1200/100) x Rnd20)<br>
<br>
Max hit = 30 + 60 + (3 x 1.2 x 20) = 192<br>
<br>
Anyone care to do some testing? 8P<br>
<br>
As for the probability of exceptional hits, I see two possibilities, either...<br>
<br>
A)  Exceptional damage is some chance on Any hit (IE, another Random roll on TOP of any hit aside from normal damage)<br>
<br>
or<br>
<br>
B)  Exceptional damage is some chance on Modal (max DB + DI) hits only.<br>
<br>
Now, my hunch is that it's done on any hit.  It would be so much simpler to program, however I'll need to get some more datapoints to confirm this (too busy doing AA and raids).  I guess I need try to find datapoints that are skewed out of the expected normal hits.<br>
<br>
Also, there may be other variables that I'm missing.  I'm not sure this formula holds true across all levels of attack.  It seems that there are some very high hit values when you get into the 1400 or 1500+ attack range.  Verant talks alot about class based damage tables and attack is a very poorly understood figure.  Could some components of attack have greater impact than others?  It seems like it's a composite of STR + Offense + Weapon skill, though it gets awful muddy with +attack items and various spells and buffs...<br>
<br>
Comments?  Ideas?<br>
<br>
LaotzuQigong<br>
60 Grandmaster<br>
Legendary<br>
